  "text": "The production Envoy proxy error 'upstream connect error or disconnect/reset before headers. reset reason: overflow' traces through multiple components:\n\n## 1. Overflow Reset Reason Definition\nThe 'Overflow' reset reason is defined as an enum value in **envoy/http/stream_reset_handler.h** with comment 'The stream was reset because of a resource overflow.' There is also a matching **PoolFailureReason::Overflow** enum in **envoy/common/conn_pool.h** (line 96-98) representing connection pool resource exhaustion.\n\n## 2. String Representation\nThe string \"overflow\" is returned by the **Utility::resetReasonToString()** function in **source/common/http/utility.cc** (lines 1030-1031) which is called as part of error message construction.\n\n## 3. Overflow Triggering Logic\nThe connection pool exhaustion is triggered in **source/common/conn_pool/conn_pool_base.cc** at two critical points:\n\n- **Line 175-180 (onStreamCreated)**: Checks if max_connections limit is exceeded via `!host_->cluster().resourceManager(priority_).requests().canCreate()`. When true, logs \"max streams overflow\" and invokes `onPoolFailure()` with `PoolFailureReason::Overflow`.\n\n- **Line 282-288 (newStreamImpl)**: Checks if max_pending_requests limit is exceeded via `!host_->cluster().resourceManager(priority_).pendingRequests().canCreate()`. When true, logs \"max pending streams overflow\" and invokes `onPoolFailure()` with `PoolFailureReason::Overflow`.\n\n## 4. Error Message Construction\nThe error message is assembled in **source/common/router/router.cc** (lines 1415-1420) in the **Filter::onUpstreamReset()** function, which constructs:\n```\n\"upstream connect error or disconnect/reset before headers. reset reason: \" + \nHttp::Utility::resetReasonToString(reset_reason) + \n\", transport failure reason: \" + transport_failure_reason\n```\nFor overflow conditions, this becomes: \"upstream connect error or disconnect/reset before headers. reset reason: overflow\"\n\n## 5. Circuit Breaker Configuration\nThe thresholds that trigger overflow are controlled by protobuf configuration in **data-plane-api**:\n\n- **envoy/config/cluster/v3/circuit_breaker.proto** (V3, active): Defines `CircuitBreakers.Thresholds` message with:\n  - `max_connections` (field 2): Maximum connections to upstream cluster, default 1024\n  - `max_pending_requests` (field 3): Maximum pending requests queue, default 1024\n  - `max_requests` (field 4): Maximum parallel requests, default 1024\n\n- **envoy/api/v2/cluster/circuit_breaker.proto** (V2, deprecated): Legacy version of the same configuration\n\n## 6. Resource Management\nThe **ResourceManagerImpl** class in **source/common/upstream/resource_manager_impl.h** (lines 74-102) enforces these limits via:\n- `connections()` method returning a ResourceLimit tied to max_connections\n- `pendingRequests()` method returning a ResourceLimit tied to max_pending_requests\n- `requests()` method returning a ResourceLimit tied to max_requests\n\nEach ResourceLimit has a `canCreate()` method that returns false when the current count reaches the configured maximum, triggering the overflow condition in the connection pool.\n\n## Summary\nWhen upstream connection pool resources are exhausted (either max active connections via requests().canCreate() or max pending queue via pendingRequests().canCreate()), the connection pool emits PoolFailureReason::Overflow, which is converted to Http::StreamResetReason::Overflow, stringified as \"overflow\" via Utility::resetReasonToString(), and embedded in the HTTP 503 error response body constructed in router.cc."
}

